Title: Mold Remediation
Description:
The crawlspace framing and subfloor has a lot of mold growth throughout
the crawlspace. It requires removing the insulation and doing a full mold
remediation, including increasing ventilation in the space through extra venting 
or mechanical venting mechanisms. We reported this problem in our pre-close 
walkthrough and were told that the builder was remediating the issue.

Description:

The installed fixture over- sprays the shower door most of the time and requires a step ladder to adjust the silicone beads every week or 2. We would like it replaced with the correct rain head.

11. The master bedroom fan control switch installed is not the one that came with the upgraded fan.  Per homeowner, the electrician installed the Kichler one and said it did not work therefore the standard wall switch was installed in its place.
12. The Kitchen lights occasionally and suddenly dim, most noticeably the island LED pendants.  Stairway lights also flicker.

Also chunks of cement have come off near garage slab, cleanup would be nice. Large scars and scabs across the asphalt, including a piece of wood embedded. There is a lot of moisture almost feels a bit like quicksand when you walk on it. ? do you want to make sure that there’s not a leak. Throughout the property, there are areas of extreme dry versus extreme wet.
5. We must replace 10 lightbulbs since we’ve been in the house for four weeks. Every time we came to the house while it was being built, we noticed the lights were on. We assumed all the lightbulbs would be replaced before we moved in. Clearly that’s not the case and now some of the ? high ceiling voltage lights have burnt out. We would like to have all new lightbulbs so that we know they will last us for a few years as they should.
6. Underneath siding (wood) is visible), electrical box and a few outside areas. The left and rear side of the exterior house needs a lot of touchups or even repaint . In particular, the exterior garage door has several issues with it screw stripped does not latch and weatherstrip is disconnect.

8. Both the large and small doors need to be repainted. Chunks of paint have peeled off.
9. I’ve had a few people mentioned to me that they noticed the lock on the front door isn’t at a straight angle. Once you see it, you always see it. I realize this is Minor and not super visible but if it’s easy to fix, I’d like it straightened.
10. There are a few places that need touchup. I believe we can also do this, but we don’t have our paint kit yet.
11. We’ve noticed several thin scratches on many of the windows, which is disappointing since they are brand new. Would like to understand what can be done. It’s difficult to capture on photo.
12. This wasn’t fully fixed during the initial walk-through when I tried to open the oven door. It’s still rubs against the quartz counter.
13. Scratches on the millwork - kitchen cabinet.
14. Back left slider - Door missing something.
15. Both back sliding glass door screens, which were installed after the initial walk-through both have holes in them. I need to be replaced..
16. Grout needs to be reapplied to the primary bathroom shower floor

Title: Misc. warranty repairs
Description:
1. Grinder pump alarm started at 9 pm on 6/20/25. What's the protocol for this type of issue? and how long do we have before we have a problem?

Also, Jack previously noted that the landscapers would stop by occasionally to ensure the new seeded areas were getting the proper amount of water. We haven't seen or talked with them. Is this still the case or is it up to us to determine when and how much to water to get things growing?
7. Water pressure seems to be on the low side at around 50 PSI (although it's around 110 PSI at the front red spigot). Is there a way to safely increase the pressure and keep within plumbing specs?
8. We could use size/model number and the instruction manual so we can set up critical Wi-Fi access. We would also like to know how to physically access the valve and electric outlet in case we need to manually reset the valve.
9. The glass door has a small gap near the wall and leaks out on the bathroom floor
10. left-side single hung window doesn't stay open and slides down 6-12 inches
11. fan timer in laundry room seems to work intermittently. might be broken or i just might need some instruction. a manual would help.
12. Laundry room door doesn't latch.
13. What circuits does the transfer switch control? and who determined which circuits would be served by the generator?
14. Garbage shed exterior door has hole from opening into pipe
15. A few drawer pulls in the kitchen are not level
16. Plans show masonry on this surface. Why/when did it change to wood siding
17. Grout is uneven and has holes in various spots as noted by contractor that provided a quote for sealing. Said this would need to be taken care of first.
18. Insurance company flagged the installation of plants off the front porch as being too close (<5ft) from the house. Replace with river rock and larger rock?
19. The garage floor is pretty high in the middle and slopes in 4 directions. Is this correct/normal?
20. The heaters appear to be angled down too much and need to be adjusted up to about 45 degrees. They also appear to be a little underpowered, but this may be related to the installation angle. Please review.
21. The ethernet cables coming into/out of the panel in the laundry closet are not terminated or at least labeled. Atlas didn't have the tools or time to figure it out when they di dthe internet install.
22. Ethernet jacks are a mixture of CAT6 and Cat5e. I think they're all supposed to be CAT6
23. Rodents have been entering the crawlspace through at least 3 damaged ventilation screens in the foundation and around gaps in the dryer vent. One screen has an attempted repair without actually fastening it to the frame. All screens should probably be evaluated. Note that mice are also entering through the gap in the garage door mentioned elsewhere.

It started the morning after the service call on Wednesday.  It can’t be heard anywhere else in the house. It sounds similar to a balloon letting air out with a pinched opening.

Title: 16. PLUMBING DRAIN, WASTE AND VENT SYSTEMS
Description:
12.0 (1) There is no evidence of a clean out access for service person's to the washing machine drain line. Typically this is a
standard installation practice in the incident of a clog/need for repair. Note that a sample photo has been attached in this
section of the report taken from another new construction home where a clean out was installed; Recommend the builder to
install a clean out access for service person's.

Title: 15. CONDENSATE DRAINAGE PROVISIONS
14. COOLING/ HEAT PUMP AND AIR HANDLER EQUIPMENT
Description:
1. The heat pump was slow to respond after initiating air-conditioning. It took approximately
10-15 minutes for the outdoor condenser to fifinally initiate the cooling cycle after AC was called
on at the thermostat.
2. The fan was slow to reach full speed. The fan motor pulsated when initially starting up, then
the RPM's were slow fifinally reaching full speed which took approximately nearly 60 seconds.

Title: 13. HEATING EQUIPMENT
Description:
There were various problematic conditions detected with the natural gas furnace at time of inspection –
see attached videos for a detailed description. Conditions are as follows:
1. The natural gas furnace/burners are "short cycling" as shown in the attached video. This is where the
burners do not complete the cycle. For example: If indoor temperatures are 68° and the thermostat is set at 75° as the desired temperature, the burners/furnace should stay on until 75° is reached. If the burners cut out prior to reaching 75°, this means the system is short cycling.
2. The condensate drain line makes a loud repetitious/constant gurgling noise as evidenced in the video and can be heard throughout the home.

Title: 12. MISC. ITEM(S)
Description: 8.11 The access hatch does not have a handle to remove and enter the crawlspace; Recommend the builder to install a permanent handle to the access hatch or a strap.

Title: 11. FIREPLACE(S)
Description:
7.7 Sidewall penetrations are not sealed under fifireplace. Cold air leaks in through the exterior direct vent, travels down the flflue
pipe in around the fifireplace and through penetrations; Recommend the builder to apply 3M tape/seal over penetrations to
minimize cold air drafts and conserve energy or upgrade insulation/repair/eliminate cold zones to improve energy effifficiency of
home.

Title: 10. ELECTRICAL
Description:
6.5 Quad receptacle at the south end of the kitchen island is loose and a safety hazard – see attached video for a
detailed description; Recommend the builder to secure the loose receptacle for safety.

Title: 9. SHOWER FIXTURES/ ENCLOSURE
Description:
5.2 (1) There is no weatherstripping on either side of the master shower enclosure door. Moisture will leak through the existing
gaps out on to the flfloor and eventually cause 'costly damage' to the construction surrounding the shower - see attached video
for a detailed description; Recommend the builder to install clear/rigid weatherstripping on both sides of door to properly
waterproof and prevent future conditions.

Title: 8. Occupant Door (from garage to inside of home)
Description:
4.7 Separation door between garage/living space is considered an exterior door and does not have a locking mechanism. If the
garage door does not close or someone hacks into the door opener – the home is accessible. This can also be a child safety
hazard i.e. (garage door is open, child exits through the door that is not lockable); The builder should install a lockable door
handle to improve home security and for child safety.

Title: 7. Garage Door (s)
Description:
4.3 There is a large gap through the center expansion joint – access point for mice/rodents/pests into the garage. Note that if
pests access the garage, they will eventually access the home which can lead to excessive damage; Recommend the builder to
seal the expansion joint gap directly below weatherstripping to prevent future conditions. Under any circumstance should this
be left open for pest activity and is "not intended for drainage". This could be easily remedied at time of construction.

Title: 6. WHOLE HOUSE FAN(S)
Description:
3.6 There were 2 problematic conditions detected in the laundry room at the time of this inspection - see attached video for a
detailed description. They are as follows:
#1. A whole house fan has been installed in this room with a solid door. Air from the whole house cannot enter this room. The
existing gap under the door is not large enough to allow enough air from the rest of the home into this room. This keeps the fan
from performing its intended function/maintain peak performance.
#2. The dryer is less effifficient without adequate make-up room air of which this vent will provide.
Recommend the builder to install a permanent natural draft vent above laundry room door as this has been a standard
construction practice for 20+ years. This allows the whole house fan to perform its intended function in providing whole house
ventilation and improves dryer effifficiency.

Title: 5. VENTILATION
Description:
Ventilation to the attic space is currently minimal. The only ventilation provisions are smart vents at the East/West sides and a Ridge vent. This might make up an accumulative total of 5 ft.² of natural draft ventilation into the attic which is very minimal. At least one square foot of ventilation is recommended for every 100-150 ft.² of attic space. Note that there is approximately 1250 ft.² of attic space which means
that there should be at least 10 ft.² of natural draft attic ventilation – see attached video for a detailed description. In addition, I conducted an inspection to the home due north of this property. The exact same ventilation provisions exist to that attic.Mold was discovered in the attic of the property due north.
I suspect that mold will result in your attic space if the builder does not improve attic ventilation;
Recommend the builder to have a licensed and bonded electrical contractor/roofifing contractor to install a high CFM output attic fan on a humidistat/thermostat in the attic space. This will require cutting out a square rooftop vent, mounting the attic fan at the underside of the vent, running electrical (inspected/approved and permitted through the city of Bothell) to the fan.

Title: 4. DRAINAGE PROVISIONS or 'LACK THEREOF'
Description:
2.11
NO DRAINAGE AT ALL ON THE PROPERTY TO HELP PREVENT PONDING STORM WATER?
There is no visible evidence of drainage provisions at the East side of home or at the North/N.E. corner areas (home sits at a low
point of the hillside). Retaining walls create a 'Well Effffect' and will trap/pool storm water. There is evidence of standing water at
this location due to absent drainage. Note that ponding water within 10' feet of the rear patio/foundation is conducive to water
penetration in the substructure, undermining of the foundation wall(s)/footing(s)/patio and potential structural movement – see
attached video for a detailed description.
NOTE:Most builder provided warranties describe a drainage problem as: 'STANDING WATER WITHIN 10' FEET OF THE
FOUNDATION FOR 72 HOURS OR MORE'. It seems that the existing conditions meets the criteria of that description;
Recommend the builder to have a licensed drainage contractor
to install drainage provisions/surface drain(s) tied in with drain
tile at this area to prevent future conditions. Slope the grade
toward the surface drains.

Title: 3. PLUMBING STACKS/ STORM BOOTS
Description: 1.8 The plumbing boot flanges are loose/lifting at the East vent stack; Recommend the builder to secure loose/lifted flflanges to prevent wind driven rain penetration/roof leakage.

Title: 1. GUTTERS/ DOWN SPOUTS/ DRAINAGE
Description:
1.4 (1) All 3 of the front second story down spouts and one at the rear discharge on the lower roof(s) - see attached video for a
detailed description. Concentrated storm water discharge is conducive to accelerated granule loss and premature roof failure;
Recommend the builder to have the roofifing contractor to extend the downspouts to discharge directly into the lower gutter(s)
to prevent accelerated decay/premature failure.

1.4 (2) Front gutter above garage is pitched incorrectly at the West end and pooling water. This is conducive to overflflow, leakage
and can weigh the gutter down resulting in detachment. Uncontrolled storm water and faulty sloped gutters can result in other
problematic conditions long-term; Recommend the builder to rehang gutter to drain correctly toward downspout to prevent
future conditions.

Title: Leaking Basement Sewer Cleanouts
Description:
We wanted to make you aware of an issue we encountered today with one of the three basement sewer cleanouts.

We contacted a licensed plumber to assess a sewer leak observed at one cleanout. During the visit, the plumber noted that all three basement cleanouts have caps installed in a reversed orientation, and that the nipple portions of the caps are pierced, which allows sewer water to escape into the basement.

As part of the assessment, the plumber also scoped the sewer line and confirmed that it is clear and functioning as intended. Based on this, the issue appears to be related to the cleanout assemblies themselves rather than any blockage or homeowner use.

The plumber did not proceed with repairs, as the appropriate replacement parts were not available and this appears to fall under the home warranty.
Given the nature of a sewer leak, we would appreciate this being addressed as soon as possible. Please let us know when your team can come out to properly reinstall or replace all three cleanouts so they are secure and no longer at risk of leaking.

We also wanted to flag that today’s plumbing service call, which was necessary to diagnose the issue, was approximately $700, and we would appreciate confirmation that this cost will be covered as part of the warranty process.

Thank you for your attention to this, and please let us know next steps and timing.

Best regards,
Brian and Diana Holloway

Title: Hot Water
Description:

The rest of the house it is pretty instantaneous for all plumbing fixtures, showers and sinks. A lot of water is wasted trying to get hot water coming. Title: Abnormally High Water Pressure
Description: I'm out of town until tomorrow, Tuesday 12/9/25. I received a high water pressure warning from my Moen Flo Smart Water Monitor this morning. It said the pressure was at 150 psi. I find that hard to believe but didn't want to take any chances. I had my neighbor go into my house and run some hot and cold faucets for a while to bleed off any extra pressure if possible. She didn't notice anything unusual. I then had her unplug the hot water circulation pump and I then shut the Moen valve remotely. I waited a few hours and opened the valve again and the pressure stabilized around 62 psi. See attached screenshot showing the monitored pressure for the last week. Was there an actual pressure issue with the PRV? Or was it just a faulty Moen valve sensor reading? Would you kindly provide some guidance on how to proceed?

Title: Dryer vent 80%+ blocked - dryer not useable
Description:
Samsung technician came this weekend to repair our Dryer which had been overheating.  They did a special test that checks the vent and confirmed that it is at least 80%+ blocked and advised this is not normal for a new house after 18 months.  They said they believe either the venting has not been designed correctly with kinks / bends in it or there is the wrong type of ending on the roof vent.  They advised us not to use the unit until this issue has been addressed as it is a potential fire hazard and will cause more issues with the dryer.

Please can you arrange for the HVAC contractor who did all the vents in the house to come out asap this week to address the issue as we cannot dry clothes properly.  

Thanks
Julien 

Mobile: 949 220 3359

Description: Furnace is malfunctioning at time of inspection –   see attached video for a detailed description. The burners are "short cycling" which means, it is not completing its cycle. The burners shut off repeatedly prior to reaching the desired set temperature at the thermostat. In addition, the furnace/heat pump are both due for annual servicing; Recommend the builder to have a licensed/qualified HVAC technician to evaluate the furnace, verify reasons for malfunction/short cycling and make all repairs needed to function correctly. While the technician is at the property, the builder needs to have the technician conduct a complete annual service to the system. Replace the air filter – should be replaced every 3-6 months.
Notes: Homeowner had private inspector check the furnace. Apparently, the furnace is cutting off heat before it reaches the set temperature. Inspector did have it on gas only.

Title: substructure does not have enough ventilation
Description: The substructure does not have enough ventilation –   see attached video for a detailed description.   There is approximately 1500 ft.² on the main floor which means there should be a total of at least 10-12 foundation vents. There are currently only 7 foundation vents which is not enough; Recommend the builder to add at least 4-6 additional foundation vents or, have a licensed electrical contractor install a substructure fan on a humidistat to improve ventilation. POOR VENTILATION IS HIGHLY CONDUCIVE TO HIGH RELATIVE HUMIDITY, CONDENSATION, MOLD, DRY ROT AND PEST DAMAGE (proper/sufficient ventilation is absolutely imperative in the substructure). Contact your local governing code authority to verify minimum substructure ventilation requirements.
Notes: I do not believe this is a warranty issue. I explained to the homeowner that the house has to pass inspection before closing on the home. If this was the case then the builder wouldn’t have gotten CO.

Title: shrinkage/expansion of the framed walls
Description: There is evidence of excessive suspect shrinkage/expansion of the framed walls, door jambs, floor joists, subfloor etc. surrounding the "separation door between the garage/living space" on the garage side – see attached video for a detailed description. The MDF trim below the threshold is canoeing/curved, door jamb molding is pulling off/separated excessively, the base of the garage wall is warped/uneven surrounding the separation door to garage. While this may potentially be structural movement due to settlement – unlikely, it is more than likely due to shrinkage/expansion of the framing surrounding the door. In addition, there are likely galvanized steel seismic straps behind the sheet rock/finish material that may be causing a pronounced finish material unevenness/separation etc.; Recommend the builder to further evaluate, remove all door jamb/trim work moldings and sheet rock where currently uneven. Verify the reasons/cause of such excessive movement to the finish materials and make all repairs needed to "prevent ongoing problematic conditions". Re-install finish materials correctly around the door and base of the North garage wall.
Notes: Door trim is protruding excessively seems like the wood behind the drywall is pushing it out, causing warpage and shrinkage to happen at the frame. ?

Title: Improper Drainage in yard
Description:
There are currently multiple areas in the yard where the ground is very saturated and just by walking on it your foot will become submerged in dirt. With multiple spots of standing water, even a day after it has stopped raining. It seems as if the French drain on the north side of the house does not work properly as there is constantly standing water. On the far west side of the lawn is also very saturated with water. The south side is also very saturated all along the foundation. 

South side: seems as if water is not draining through the dirt that is below the gravel. All along the foundation anything bearing weight will sink into the ground. Also along the backyard patio is the same issue, worried about foundation issues long term. 

West side of lawn: along the west perimeter of the lawn is all saturated. Causing the grass to slowly die. Worried about potential long term issues with the retaining wall. 

North side: the entire north side of the yard is a marsh pit. It seems as if the French drain is barely working even after cleaning around it. All along the retaining wall the ground compresses when stepped on. Very worried about issues with the retaining wall. And there is major standing water. 

Front yard: due to the issues in the side yards, the front yard is also having saturation issues. 

We are wanting to remedy these issues. It is not allowing us to put up sheds as we are worried about it sinking into the ground.

Is this something that can be addressed via our warranty? We have only been in the house for less than 3 weeks and experiencing this pretty big issue.

Title: Whole House Fan vent
Description:
There were 2 problematic conditions detected in the laundry room at the time of this inspection -   see attached video for a detailed description. They are as follows:
#1. A whole house fan has been installed in this room with a solid door. Air from the whole house cannot enter this room. The existing gap under the door is not large enough to allow enough air from the rest of the home into this room. This keeps the fan from performing its intended function/maintain peak performance.

#2. The dryer is less efficient without adequate make-up room air of which this vent will provide.

Recommend the builder to install a permanent natural draft vent above laundry room door as this has been a standard construction practice for 20+ years. This allows the whole house fan to perform its intended function in providing whole house ventilation and   improves dryer efficiency.
Notes: Builder does not add a vent here.

White efflorescence staining was found along the base of the East foundation wall indicating a history of storm water leaching under the home; Recommend the builder to have a licensed and bonded drainage contractor to evaluate and install at least 2 surface drains along the east side of the home. Slope the grade toward the drains to properly divert storm water. Monitor substructure for future moisture intrusion. Obtain warranty information from the builder that clearly describes builder responsibility in the incident of future moisture intrusion. A minimum 5 year warranty issued by the builder to the home homeowner is recommended.

Title: EAVES/ SOFFITS Block (Code violation)
Description: The builder blocked off the neighbors soffit vents (just west of this property) but not the West soffit vents on this home? Why? Is this a current fire separation code violation? – See attached video for a detailed description. Typically, when homes are constructed in close proximity (as they are currently), soffit vents must be blocked off for fire separation reasons; Recommend the builder to show the homeowner the existing code. What is the distance requirement in your area for soffit vents to be blocked? What is the current distance between your home and the neighbors property? Why did the builder block off the neighbors and not yours? These questions need to be clearly answered by the builder and disclose to the homeowner. Contact your local governing residential code authority to verify the minimum code requirement – make sure your builder is meeting the code.

Title: conditions detected with the HVAC system
Description:
There were various conditions detected with the HVAC system at time of inspection –   see attached video for a detailed description. Conditions are as follows:
1. The natural gas furnace and electric heat pump are both due for annual servicing.
2. The builder left behind excessive construction debris/sheet rock dust buildup in the furnace combustion area. This is highly conducive to result in HVAC system malfunction, short cycling etc.
3. The HVAC system installer did not install a "sediment drip leg" to the natural gas line – this is a potential safety hazard, more than likely in violation of minimum code requirements and can result in system malfunction.
Recommend the builder to have a licensed and bonded "qualified" HVAC technician to conduct a complete annual service to the furnace/heat pump, remove construction debris from the combustion area (vacuum out the ductwork), install bushings at the gas line bypass and finish sediment drip leg installation for safety. The condition mentioned in section 10 point below should also be corrected at time of service.
Notes: Homeowner have private inspection. Inspector noted conditions of the HVAC system. Please advise.

Title: Ventilation issues in Laundry room
Description:
There were 3 problematic conditions detected in the laundry room at the time of this inspection -   see attached video for a detailed description. They are as follows:
#1. A whole house fan has been installed in this room with a solid door. Air from the whole house (rooms outside the laundry room) cannot enter this room. The existing gap under the door is not large enough to allow enough air from the rest of the home into this room. This keeps the fan from performing its intended function.

#2. The laundry room is an unconditioned space, no heat source currently.

#3. The dryer is less efficient without adequate make-up room air of which this vent will provide.

The builder should install a permanent natural draft vent above laundry room door as this is a very common practice in most of today's new construction and has been for the last 20+ years. This vent helps supply warm air from the condition space to the unconditioned space. This also allows the whole house fan to perform its intended function in providing whole house ventilation and improves dryer efficiency.
Notes: Homeowner had a private inspection. Inspector noted that there should be a vent to allow airflow please see pictures.

Title: NO DRAINAGE PROVISIONS  on Hillside south
Description:
The entire Hillside South of the home slopes toward this property (NO DRAINAGE PROVISIONS EXIST). A retaining wall has been installed at the south property line and creates a "well effect" between the retaining wall and foundation wall. This is highly conducive to pool water directly next to the foundation wall and result in:
Storm water intrusion in the crawlspace.
Soggy/swampy conditions along the south side of property.
Undermining of the foundation, structural movement and costly conditions.
If moisture enters the substructure, this can result in high relative humidity, condensation, mold, fungi, pest damage etc.
NOTE: In the Northwest, proper drainage control around the home is absolutely essential and imperative to prevent future costly problematic conditions.

Recommend the builder to have a licensed and bonded/professional drainage contractor to install drainage provisions at the South side of home. Install at least two surface drains (slope the grade toward the drains) or, install a French drain extending east/west of the full length of the foundation along the south side of home.

Title: Sewer Gas
Description:
Significant new presence of sewage smell outside from of home 8045B of Shelter II as of Friday September 26th (morning), increased and continued through today (September 27th). Smell was present that morning, yesterday evening, last night, and this morning.

A sewer clog at a presumed root ball was cleared about 2 months ago (end of June). There was some sewage smell after that did mostly dissipate, but not to this degree. Given new strong smell with persistence, worry it may be the same issue reappearing and understand it would qualify as an emergency given potential for damage.

Also concerned about possible leak given the persistence of smell after the previous clog, and repeated sinking of pavers around the sewer cleanout in our patio at move in and about a month after, continued through today, after previous clog.

Title: Laundry Room Needs Air Vent

Notes: This is built to spec builder is not required to install a vent.

Title: Dryer Duct Not Insulated in Attic
Description: Rigid galvanized dryer duct in attic not wrapped with insulation, causing heat loss and condensation potential per IMC M1601.4.6. Required remediation: Wrap dryer duct with appropriate insulation.

Title: Retaining Wall Blocks Damaged

Title: Front Stoop Fractured Corner

Title: Condensate Lines Not Insulated
Description: Water heater and furnace condensate lines uninsulated in unconditioned garage space, susceptible to freezing per IMC 307.2.3. Required remediation: Insulate condensate drain lines to prevent freezing and equipment malfunction.
Notes: I do not think builders typically put insulation on these pipes only water pipes as seen in this picture. Please advise.

Title: No Water Pressure Regulator
Description: No visible pressure regulator at main water entry. IPC 608.2 requires pressure-reducing valve when supply exceeds 80 psi. Required remediation: Licensed plumber to install pressure regulator or builder to disclose location if installed elsewhere
Notes: Inspector noted no PRV valve installed at main water shut please advise.

Title: Kitchen Cabinet Shelves Need Corbels
Description: Upper cabinet shelves spanning 32"+ lack corbels, creating collapse hazard. Required remediation: Install corbels to prevent shelf failure.
Notes: Inspector noted that there should be supports to hold the middle of the shelf because it spans over 32 inches.

Title: Downspouts Discharge on Lower Roof
Description: Both front second-story downspouts discharge concentrated water on lower roof, causing accelerated granule loss and premature failure. Required remediation: Extend downspouts to discharge directly into lower gutters to prevent accelerated deterioration.
Notes: This is built to spec and builder is not required to extend the down spout to the gutter.

Title: Plumbing Vent Stack Too Short
Description: S.E. plumbing vent stack only 4" above roof deck, susceptible to snow blockage. IRC P3103.1 requires minimum 6" in areas with snow. Required remediation: Adjust vent stack height to minimum 8"+ to match other stacks and prevent blockage.
Notes: Homeowner had a private inspection. Inspector noted that the vent stack is only 4” and needs to be 6-8” please advise.

Title: Floors Out of Level - Structural
Description: Floors crowning/out of level in loft hallway and kitchen by sliding door. Builder warranty typically defines structural defect as "1/4" variation over 32" span." Required remediation: Check with 6-foot level. If exceeding 1/4" over 32", licensed structural contractor must evaluate cause and repair floors to level per IRC R802.
Notes: I put my level on the flooring up stairs according to the level there are some areas where the bubble is more towards the left as you can see in the 32 inch level. Inspector also recommended for me to use a 6 foot level. I did bring a 6 foot level as you will see in the picture the bubble is in the middle.

Title: Master Shower Door No Weatherstrip
Description: No weatherstripping on either side of master shower door. Water will leak through gaps causing costly damage to surrounding construction. Required remediation: Install clear/rigid weatherstripping on both sides of door to properly waterproof enclosure.
Notes: Inspector noted that should be weather tripping or splash at tile to shower door.

Title: Insufficient Crawlspace Vents
Description: Only 7 foundation vents installed for 3500+ sq ft home (minimum 1500 sq ft main floor requires 10+ vents per IRC R408.1 - 1 sq ft per 150 sq ft crawlspace). Current installation may violate minimum code requirements. Insufficient ventilation causes moisture damage, mold growth, and structural deterioration. Required remediation: Licensed contractor to install 3-5 additional foundation vents. Evidence of mold existing on crawl space beams.
Notes: Homeowner had a private inspection. Inspectors noted that there are not enough foundation vents. Please advise.

Title: Attic Has Zero Ventilation
Description: ower Southeast enclosed attic space has NO ventilation source, violating IRC R806.1 requiring minimum 1 sq ft ventilation per 150 sq ft attic space. Additionally, main attic temperatures exceed 130°F (40°+ above outdoor temp), indicating severe under-ventilation. Required remediation: Install ventilation sources (smart vents/rooftop vents) in SE attic space. Install attic fan on humidistat/thermostat for main attic. Contact City of Bothell for inspection to verify code compliance. Obtain electrical permits for fan installation.
Notes: Homeowner had a private inspection. Inspector noted insufficient ventilation of attic. Inspector mentioned that there should be fan installed or no vent at gable be vent. No daylight coming through. Only ridge vents and smart vents Please advise.

Title: No Site Drainage - Foundation Risk
Description: Inadequate provisions  on the property. The front yard slopes toward the foundation with evidence of standing water within 10 feet of the foundation. This violates IRC R401.3 requiring lots to be graded to drain surface water away from foundation walls (minimum 6" fall within first 10 feet). Builder warranty criteria defines this as "standing water within 10 feet of foundation for 72+ hours." Required remediation: Licensed drainage contractor must install French/curtain drain in front yard and surface drains at all other locations, properly connected to drain tile. Grade must be sloped away from foundation.
Notes: Homeowner mentioned that there’s is inadequate drainage at the front of his house. The inspector noted that he has a negative slope going towards his front patio. Inspector noted that there should be a yard drain so water does not pull up in this area. He also mentioned that the back yard does not have proper drainage and that water does not drain well. During my inspection there were no signs of water. Please advise.

Title: Garage Door
Description:
1. Garage door openers have a sensor that will reverse if there is too much pressure to prevent the crushing of an object. The garage door did not reverse when pressure was applied to the door. It is difficult to open with this low position of the handle without causing me lower back pain.    Thermador shows this freezer drawer handle near the top of the drawer.  I am happy to send you pics if needed.  DeWaard Bode installer has told me he can replace the panels once new panels are ordered for the top of fridge cabinet and freezer drawer to match existing. The freezer door will need a new panel, not a hole filled in the current one.   If you have any questions about this item please contact the installer Trevor from DB.  Thank you

Fran Kahler

Title: Bowed West-Facing Window Frames
Description:
Observed during a new inspection on 8/4/2025, from inspector:

A majority of the west facing windows frames in the home have warped and are pulling away from the window. The home owner states that with a little wind the windows rattle and vibrate. These vibrations mean that the window is not set into the frame as the manufacture has intended and will get worse over time leaving room for possible moisture intrusion. I recommend the builder evaluate the windows on the home and make repairs to the window frame so that the windows are secure to the home. The home owner has sense filled silicone into the gap to stop the vibrations.

--
In addition, we have had PlyGem replace one of the windows twice, because of the rattling. Second time they recommended to use silicone to hold it in place, but that failed within an hour from the most recent replacement (7/28/2025).

Title: False smoke alarm twice
Description:
I understand that warranty submissions are ideally completed by now, but this issue just occurred today and has actually happened a few times before.

This afternoon, my neighbor notified me that the smoke alarm in my home was going off. I had to leave work early, and the alarm continued sounding for nearly two hours with repeated three-beep alerts. After checking everything, it seems to have been a false alarm.

The model in question is the Kidde 900-CUAR. After looking online, I found many other people reporting the exact same issue—false alarms with the same beep pattern.  See: https://www.kidde.com/products/combo-alarms/self-testing-hardwired-smoke-carbon-monoxide-alarm     

I have several interconnected alarms installed, and the one in the living room seems to be the source of the problem.

I’ve tried reaching out to Kidde but haven’t been able to get a response. I wanted to check with you to see if there’s anything you can do to help with this, or if there’s a way to get support through your channels.

Thanks for your time and assistance
Notes: Homeowner believes that these two smoke alarms are faulty. He has changed the batteries but they still go off. Also the red flashing lights indicates that there is a problem with the unit.

Title: Addendum to Electrical warranty issues
Description:
Subject: Addendum to Electrical Warranty Items

Please consider this an addendum to the existing list of electrical warranty items for your records.

We have experienced multiple electrical issues in our home, both past and ongoing. Most recently, the non-functioning fireplace switch in the living room was addressed and resolved by the fireplace company.  
Last fall a faulty GFI outlet in the garage tripped the breaker. This incident affected seven outlets after an appliance was plugged in. This occurred shortly after we moved in and at the time, MCE was working at a neighboring property, and I asked their electrician to take a look. Initially, he was unsure of the cause but ultimately determined the GFI outlet was defective and replaced it.

Given this and the other electrical concerns we’ve encountered, we are increasingly concerned that there may be a broader, systemic electrical issue within the home.

Title: Electrical issues
Description:
This warranty item was on a previous claim and it has not been fully looked into and the issue still exists.  The Kitchen lights occasionally and suddenly dim, most noticeably the island LED pendants.  The refrigerator App (Thermador Home Connect) has sent 3-5 notifications over the past several months of a “low voltage” issue.  My refrigerator camera features have not worked since day one so I have been in touch with customer service about troubleshooting.   This is a separate issue.  I informed them also of a low voltage notification and I am attaching their response.  I will also add that we once had “flashing” pendant lights in our staircase when we had a guest using the guest bedroom outlet charger.  
I plan to contact MCE Electric today.

Title: Foundation / Soil Instability Behind Property
Description:
I am writing to submit a warranty claim regarding potential structural and soil stability issues at my home.

In the area behind my backyard, which slopes down into a conservation easement, I have observed significant soil cracking and surface displacement. Most concerning is that one of the fence posts adjacent to this area has visibly tilted, suggesting possible ground movement or erosion that may affect the property's stability.

This area has no development due to its protected status, and there are no obvious drainage controls. I am concerned this may reflect a foundational or grading issue related to the original construction.

Title: Added to claim 0002
Description:
While configuring our home internet network I tested several of the house-wired Ethernet outlets with a handheld RJ-45 cable-continuity tester (the kind with a MASTER and REMOTE unit that lights an LED for each of the eight pins).

How I tested:
Plugged the MASTER unit into one of the cat5 cables in the master bedroom closet networking panel
Plugged the REMOTE unit into the matching wall jack in each room.
Watched the LEDs cycle 1 ? 8.
• If all eight pins are connected, every LED lights in sequence.
• If a pin is open, its LED never lights.

I first confirmed the tester on a spare patch cable (all eight LEDs lit), then checked four wall jacks:
- One of the wall jacks correctly has all eight pins connected, and the wired internet connection behaves as expected. 
- For each of the other 3 tested, one of the pins was not connected (pin #3 for one, pin #5 for another, etc). When even one pin is open, the drop cannot provide a fully functional Ethernet connection.  

Because multiple drops are mis-terminated, I’d like you to send someone to:
1. Test every Ethernet run with an eight-pin RJ-45 continuity tester (T-568B wiring).
2. Re-terminate both ends of any run that fails, so every outlet operates correctly, then test the run again and confirm that all eight pins are connected.

Title: Drain pan needed for the water heater
Description:
No drain pan has been installed below the water heater here. A drain pan is recommended under water heaters that are located in finished spaces or where a leak could damage finishes. Where a pan does not already exist, the tricky part is providing a drain to the outside. A pan without a drain is often of limited benefit/protection. For improved protection from accidental water heater leaks, and where a drain is difficult to install, consider a pan with a moisture alarm and a flood-safe device.

Title: Siding too close to ground
Description: Siding or trim in contact with the ground or soil is a concern because it can provide direct access for wood destroying insects and or moisture. It is recommended to maintain a minimum ground clearance of 4" from the ground and 2" from hardscapes. The key is to give the siding/trim some clearance so that it can drip dry and not remain wet for an entire season or all year long even. It is also recommended to have a 2% grade to help drain any surface water away from the house.
Notes: This is not a warranty issue.

Title: Temperature imbalance
Description:
The downstairs is noticeably colder than the main level above even after attempts to trim/adjust the heat vents to direct warm air downstairs.  
At the 11-month claims evaluation appointment on 2/21/24, the main floor thermostat was set at 67 degrees, the adjacent room read 69.2 degrees, the downstairs room read 62.4 degrees, and the 3rd floor read 72.1. 

Variation in temperatures is affected by many variables such as sun exposure to rooms, leaving interior doors open or closed.  A variance between adjacent floors shouldn't exceed 7 degrees.  Temperature readings at the time of evaluation did not exceed this tolerance.  Please see the attached document explaining heat balance.  No warranty action necessary.

Title: Plumbing emergency - Repairs requested
Description:
Good afternoon, 

I am writing to inform you about an emergency plumbing situation at 3934 B South Pearl St, Seattle, WA 98118, as well as to request compensation and repairs consistent with the agreement outlined in the Builder's Limited Warranty.

At approximately 6pm on Wednesday 9/25/2024, we discovered that the bathtub in the downstairs bathroom was filling with sewage. To avoid it overflowing and causing damage to other parts of the house, we called an emergency plumber from Bee's Plumbing and Heating. Upon arrival, the plumber stated that the mainline was backing up. To fix this problem, they attempted to snake the mainline and in doing so observed that the backwater valve was stuck shut - meaning that water was not able to flow from the house to the main sewer line. As they noted (see attached), this backwater valve was faulty and needs to be replaced. The plumber removed this valve so that water is able to flow from the house to the sewer. This valve is no longer functioning and, as a result, backwater is now potentially able to cause flooding. 

Yesterday's repairs cost $1,981.06, which we paid out of pocket. We are seeking reimbursement for this cost given that this problem falls under Section B Coverage (which lasts 2 years - and we are within this period), specifically I. Mechanical systems, 1. Plumbing, water supply, and septic systems, f. stopped up sewers, fixtures, and drains. As stated in the Builder's Limited Warranty document (Section VI, C), the homeowner should not make any voluntary payments without written approval of the builder. However, our out-of-pocket expenses fall under the exception written in the same section which states that these expenses may be paid without written approval in making repairs in an emergency condition, provided that (1) these repairs are solely for the protection of the home from further damage, (2) we notify the builder of these repairs within 5 days, and (3) we provide the builder with an accurate written record of the repair costs (see attached for PDF of the repair costs). Our situation meets all of these requirements. 

Additionally, we request that the builder repair, or provide compensation for repair, the backwater valve. Bee’s Plumbing and Heating quoted these repairs at $6,038.15. Please see attached for a PDF of this quote. 

As backwater valves are required by the City of Seattle, it is vital that this is repaired immediately. After submitting this written documentation, I will attempt to call the builder requesting repairs. I am able to be reached by phone at (505)550-5387 or by email at tjjflc@gmail.com. 

Attached are the required documents, including the costs of yesterday’s repairs and the quoted cost for the backwater valve repairs. 

Thank you,
Tyler Jimenez
Homeowner of 3934 B South Pearl St, Seattle, WA 98118
Notes:
Emailed HO 10/10 to update them on reimbursement status. JS
back flow valve replaced 10/16/24 completed

We look forward to this issue being addressed and rectified very soon.

Title: Plumbing issue at 567 NE 90th St.
Description:
Last Friday (12/6), the toilet on the first floor of my house became completely clogged. Prior to the clogging, the toilet had been gurgling intensely. A similar issue occurred about two weeks ago but resolved itself within a few hours. Unfortunately, this time, the clog persisted, and using a plunger had no effect.

I contacted Beacon Plumbing on Friday evening, and they suggested that the problem might be due to a backed-up mainline requiring specialized equipment to clear, with an estimated cost of $805. I paid $82.76 for the trip charge but decided to seek a second opinion from another plumbing company.

On Saturday (12/7), Pioneer Plumbing inspected the issue and identified the cause as a problem with the backwater valve for the sewer line. An additional flap at the bottom of the valve body was causing toilet paper to accumulate. The plumber removed the extra flap piece and reinstalled the flap assembly. The total cost for their service was $461.21.

Title: Plumbing backup
Description:
Dear Team,

I am the homeowner of Lot 16 in Bothell Paisley. My new home was closed on September 30, 2024, and within less than 60 days, I am already facing sewer drain clogging issues caused by gravel inside the pipeline. This has been an extremely unpleasant experience, and I have not received adequate support from the builder to resolve the problem.

Here is a timeline of the events:

November 20, 2024: Water backed up in the first-floor bathroom, which I had to clean.
November 21, 2024: Cascade Builder Service scheduled a plumber to inspect the issue. The plumber determined the problem was in the main sewer line outside the property and mentioned escalating the matter to their manager for the next steps.
November 21, 2024: The water backup occurred again in the first-floor bathroom.
November 22, 2024: I hired a plumber to address the clog temporarily. The builder later sent someone to confirm that the gravel in the pipeline was the root cause.

I have had to take several days off work to deal with this issue, and I am deeply frustrated by the lack of updates or resolution from the builder. The pipeline remains partially obstructed, and another water backup could happen at any time.

I am requesting immediate assistance to resolve this issue with high priority. Please provide an update on the next steps as soon as possible.

Title: Mitsubishi air conditioner leaking water
Description:
Hi.  My Mitsubishi system in the master bedroom is leaking water.  It was coming out pretty good but now just dripping 

The HVAC contractor inspected the mini split unit in the master bedroom and it is in working order for both heating and cooling at this time.  There was no obvious issue with the ceiling unit and the contractor suspects that it was some type of malfunction related to the power outage causing the outdoor compressor to activate the A/C function and cause the internal coil to freeze when the unit was off. He believes the melting ice overwhelmed or clogged the drip pan pump which led to the water dripping from the ceiling unit. The drip pan is now dry and no repairs were necessary at this time.

Title: SANCO2 Water Heater Replacement
Description:
Per message sent to homeowner on 7/11/24, this reimbursement request has been declined under warranty.  This claim was submitted after the one year warranty expiration date and, also, the warranty provisions don't allow for homeowners to make repairs on their own and request reimbursement.

On 3/29/24 I had my leaking SANCO2 Water Heater (see picture) replaced by a natural gas tankless water heater.  DeJong Heating did the work (see invoice), replacing the old heat pump water heater with a Navien NP-210A2 97% tankless natural gas water heater.  The total came to $6,032.58.  I did some research and found that the company that made the SANCO2 water heater is no longer doing business in the United States and relocated to Australia, though I see some third-party businesses still trying to sell this defective product online.  Also, my one-year warranty period did not end till June 8, 2014, so my claim is well within the warranty period.

In addition, over a dozen of my Woods Point neighbors have had to replace their SANCO2 for the same reason at their own expense. Unfortunately, for many of them, their tanks started to leak just a short time after their (1) warranty expired.

I am asking for some type of reimbursement for the costs I incurred.  Had Landed Gentry offered to repair the old heater or replace it with the same thing, I definitely would have rejected that offer.  I would ask that you give serious consideration to my claim as you will probably receive similar ones from other Woods Point residents that had to deal with the same problem.  

Thank you.

Herbert G. Porter
1360 Woods Point Loop
Ferndale, WA 98248
360-820-2547

Title: *Negative slope toward foundation & Crawlspace
Description:
1. Negative slope toward foundation noted at front right perimeter & Lower Right perimeter. Would like to inquire with builder regarding
drainage system components, layout, etc. (if any). Evidence of moisture entry is apparent in the
crawlspace during time of inspection. Negative slope toward foundation also noted at lower right perimeter causes water to pool at the base
of the foundation during heavy rainstorm.

Drainage systems were installed per code and received final approval from the jurisdictional authority prior to closing.  No standing water noted in the crawl space.

2. Plank serving as footing for crawlspace access ladder was cracked, allowing ladder to sway slightly
when in use. Recommend replacement with approved materials as required to steady ladder base.

There is no warranty provision for this.  No warranty action necessary.

3. Evidence of moisture entry was apparent in the crawlspace at time of inspection in the form of small
puddles noted on top of vapor barrier, damp and softened soil below vapor barrier and muddy high
water mark visible on lower rear interior foundation wall. Negative slope toward foundation noted at
front right exterior perimeter may allow moisture to pool against foundation and enter crawlspace.
Excessive moisture in the underbuilding may be condition conducive to structural settlement, wood destroying organism infestation and rusting of mechanical
components. Review of provisions for exterior and crawlspace moisture management should be
conducted including downspout extensions, swales, redirecting landscape watering patterns and/or
installation of underground drainage systems. If standing water cannot be eliminated with passive
systems, we recommend installation of gravel surrounded sump-pit(s) containing submersible sump
pump(s). Recommend further evaluation by a qualified, licensed contractor and repair as required to
eliminate excess subterranean moisture.

No standing water is present in the crawl space.  Evidence of past water is likely from initial construction before framing went up.  No warranty action necessary.

4. Cellulose debris noted at a handful of crawlspace locations. Cellulose debris is any wood or wood
byproduct material of a size that can be raked or larger. Recommend removal to prevent conditions
hospitable to wood destroying organisms.

There is no warranty provision for this.  Recommend homeowner removes the small pieces of wood if concerned. 

5. Small crack noted at foundation wall interior in rear right crawlspace area. Would like sealing with a high
quality urethane caulking material as required to prevent prevent moisture intrusion and further
widening of cracks due to winter freeze/thaw cycles.

Hairline cracks in foundation walls are normal and expected.  No warranty action necessary.

Title: *Kitchen plumbing details/insulation
Description:
Plumbing to the kitchen sink, dishwasher and the Northeast exterior hose bib all FROZE, leaving them with no water during the winter season.

The plumbing to the kitchen could not be located from within the crawlspace at the time of inspection due to excessive insulation and structural obstructions –   see attached video for a detailed description;  

We request to please locate the plumbing to the kitchen under the home. Check to ensure that the plumbing is properly insulated. The area of concern is at the "vertical plumbing within the East exterior wall". This area is physically/visibly inaccessible and proper installation love plumbing installation was not verified. Note that the plumbing needs to be installed on the "heated side of the insulation" within the wall. 

Note that frozen plumbing can result in pipe breakages, flooding and excessive water damage to the surrounding construction.

Pips may freeze during extreme low temperatures and this is not covered under the warranty provisions.

Title: *Missing insulation to condensate drain line
*Missing insulation
*HVAC heating issue
Description:
After approximately 45+ minutes of continual heat pump cycle time, maximum temperatures reached on "heat mode" where approximately 95°-98° at the registers. This is on the low end in comparison to the recommended temperature range is 110° minimum. If outdoor temperatures are 45° and cooler, 95° temperature output at the registers from the heat pump is not warm enough to adequately heat the home. This can cause the heat pump to the cycle continuously, drive up energy costs, decrease the lifespan of the heat pump due to over-use and may ultimately leave the home feeling uncomfortable/cold. It seems to be underperforming on heat mode.

This is what we observed in the last winters too where we even complained about the house not heating well enough even at higher temperatures. 

Please send a technician to evaluate and determine reasons/cause of low temperature output on "heat mode". Make all repairs needed to produce warm air temperatures in the 110° + range to improve energy efficiency of the system.

The warranty provisions state - A heating system shall be capable of producing an inside temperature of at least 70-degrees Fahrenheit as measured in the 
center of the room at a height of 5 feet above the floor under local outdoor winter design conditions. No warranty action necessary.

Title: *Vent doesnt meet standards for ventilation CO gas
Description:
During 11 month inspection, the inspector noted a metal B-vent on the lower section of roof on the back side of the structure. This vent does not meet current code or what is allowable for safe ventilation of carbon monoxide gas. According to the Washington State mechanical code for chimneys and vents: All vertical termination vents for gas appliances need to comply with the following requirements below. 
1. Where the vent termination is located below an adjacent roof structure , the termination point shall be located not less than 3 feet (914 mm) from such structure- The vent is located below the adjacent roof structure and the current space between the vent and the structure is less than 3 feet.
2. The vent shall terminate not less than 4 feet (1219 mm) below, 4 feet (1219 mm) horizontally from or 1 foot (305 mm) above any door, window or gravity air inlet for the building. - The current vent is less than 4 feet horizontally and does not exhaust above the adjacent window at all.

The home met all applicable building codes at the time of closing.  Attached is the installation instructions for the B vent.  No warranty action necessary.

recommend blowing out the system every winter for proper care and maintenance. If there is no blow out

*It's also important to make sure you know if you are required by your local jurisdiction to test your
double check valve annually.

System and valves were shut off when I arrived. 
I showed the homeowner the location of the valves, how to turn the system back on and ran him through the basics of the Rainbird panel.
The homeowner wants to be connected with the landscaping company. 
It appeared he had not used the system all year. 
No warranty issues noted at this time.

Title: Insulating furnace water drain pipe

Insulating the outside of the house end highly like will not be enough. Insulating the entire pipe is expected. Because of pipe not being insulated, freezing the drain pipe and causing water leak may comeback again. I think this is something builder should have done during the construction time.

We have also cleaned up all the standing water in the room and put fans and heaters in the laundry room. We've also pulled back the carpet that was soaked by the transition and used towels to dry as best as possible. We've then pulled back the carpet padding that was also soaked and have placed a heating fan directly on it.

Title: Decking code concerns
Description:
18. Deck missing tension ties within 12" of
each end of deck where ledger and joist
connect. Current deck should have a total
of 4 even spaced from end lateral ties
(tension ties) See R507.9.2

19. Insufficient ledger anchors were present,
with only a single ledger anchor per bay,
Add additional ledgers anchors in the
correct anchor pattern (fig provided
507.9.3.1(1) to meet minimum code
anchoring requirements. IRC section 507
Decks. Note one black ledger anchor per bay, add
additional. Note Nails are subject to
withdrawal.

20. Missing joist hanger at South end of deck
where gas line was set adjacent to joist.
(Note overnailing can weaken a
connection)

21. Beam at SE corner of deck was missing
fasteners. Add appropriate fasteners to
secure as required by hardware
manufacture to meet code. See attached
fastener and nail hole guide.

22. Joist Hanger not installed due to over cut
ledger from hasty un-workmanlike manner
installation of deck ledger board, due to
interference by an exhaust Damper. Have
corrections made so joist hanger is
installed as required.
Contractors could of used a closed flange
hanger for application, yet failed to adapt
for situation.

23. Beam and joist connections were missing
strapping/hurricane clips (H1 or H2 clips)
used to prevent uplift or Bounding deck in
a seismic zone. (Western Washington is in
a D2 seismic zone). Have required
strapping installed to bring up to current
regional building requirements.

24. Stair stringer not properly secured to deck
and does not meet minimum attachment
requirements. Install 2X material at cut
ends of stringer see pic, then add steel
strapping to correct.

25. Base of Stair stringer were short and not
properly supported, with untreated cut
ends in contact with concrete. Have
stringer base positively connected to pad.
Builder inspector not opposed to shimming
with either cedar of synthetic shims, due
to low liability. Do best to treat ends with
minimal clearance, and not stain concrete.
Stringer not positively connected.

26. Cut ends of pressure treated wood /
building materials to be used at exterior of
home, are required to be treated with
exterior wood preservative.( R3170101
Field treatment)
Seal ripped board on untreated exposed
side. Note: untreated cut ends, can decay over
time if left open to weather in the PNW.

Title: *Roofing channel
Description:
The West front Valley just West of the garage is "too narrow" at the bottom and was designed poorly –   see attached video for a detailed description. As it is currently, and as it was called out in the first inspection report as a "problem area", excessive debris, ice, moisture is currently accumulating at the bottom of the valley due to a narrow channel. Debris, ice/moisture is currently damming/backing up within this narrow channel which can cause ponding water and drive moisture under the shingle drip edges. This is highly conducive to near future roof failure; Recommend the builder to have a licensed and bonded/professional roofing contractor (third party non-affiliate preferred), to evaluate and determine the proper course of remedial action. Anticipate invasive repair to open up/widen the base of the Valley to allow unobstructed debris/moisture to freely exit to the gutter and prevent future debris accumulation/problematic conditions.

There is no warranty provision for this.  Severe lack of homeowner maintenance was observed.  Significant amount of tree debris is collecting on the roof.  No warranty action necessary.

Title: *Downspouts discharge on roof
Description:
The front porch second story down spout discharges on the lower roof. Both front upper Northeast gutters discharge on the lower roof similarly. There is excessive algae/mildew build up on the shingles and already evidence of granule loss after less than 12 months. The downspouts should be extended to discharge directly in the lower gutter(s). The second story gutter ends should be closed off and down spouts added to discharge directly in the lower gutters. Concentrated storm water discharge resulting in streaming is conducive to accelerated granule loss and premature roof failure – see attached video for a detailed description. Regardless of code, the roof changes from a 'thirty-year roof' to a '10 year roof' at these faulty gutter/downspout discharge locations; Recommend the builder to have the roofing contractor extend the downspout to discharge directly in the lower gutters. Modify/reconfigure the Northeast second-story gutters to avoid discharging on the lower roof material.

There is no warranty provision for this.  As shown in the attached video, there is a significant lack of homeowner maintenance.  Significant algae buildup and tree debris has collected on the roof.  No warranty action necessary.

Title: *Poor countertop installation
Description:
The under mount sink was not installed/supported correctly at the flanges at the underside of countertop. The sink is essentially "glued only" to the underside of countertop with a two wood shims at the left/right sides. Sink is highly susceptible to detachment; Recommend the builder to have a licensed/qualified contractor to install 2 brackets on each side of the sink (8 total). Or install support straps under the sink. Or install properly displaced wood bracing with brackets at the front/rear cabinet structure on the left/right side of the sink mounted securely under the sink flanges. NOTE: There are multiple ways to properly secure the sink, existing mounting method is not recommended.

There is no warranty provision for this.  The sink is secured and no movement was observed.
